Project Python Foundations: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost_of_the_order: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Observations:¶

  1. Cost of the Order Distribution: The cost of orders is right-skewed, with most orders falling in the $10–$15 range. Boxplot: The boxplot confirms the concentration of order costs around the median of approximately $15. There are some higher-cost outliers, suggesting premium orders or large group purchases.

  2. Food Preparation Time Distribution: Food preparation times are evenly distributed, with a noticeable clustering around every 5-minute interval, indicating batch-based or standardized cooking times. Boxplot: The interquartile range is narrow (~25 to 31 minutes), with a median around 28 minutes, implying controlled kitchen processes. Insight: Consistent prep times are good for operational predictability. Further reductions in prep time could enhance efficiency.

  3. Delivery Time Distribution: Delivery time shows a slight right-skew, with a peak near 25–28 minutes, but a broader spread than prep time. Boxplot: The median delivery time is ~26 minutes. A wider spread and a few high-end values suggest logistical inconsistencies, possibly due to distance, traffic, or surge hours.

  4. High Volume of Missing Ratings: The category "Not given" has the highest count among all rating values, indicating that a significant proportion of customers did not provide feedback. This missing information could skew insights if not handled appropriately and suggests a gap in user engagement post-delivery. Be cautious when analyzing satisfaction trends—since only a subset of users rated their experience, the current distribution may not be fully representative.

  5. Higher Order Volume on Weekends: The number of orders placed on weekends significantly exceeds those on weekdays. This indicates that customer activity spikes during the weekend, likely due to increased leisure time and dining out behavior.

  6. Dominance of American, Japanese, and Italian Cuisine: American cuisine has the highest number of orders, followed closely by Japanese and Italian. These top three categories likely represent customer favorites or are more widely available on the platform.

Observations: After removing rows with non-informative "Not given" ratings and converting the remaining ratings to numeric values, the correlation heatmap reveals that the numerical variables in the dataset exhibit very weak linear relationships with one another.¶

  1. The delivery time shows a slight negative correlation with cost of the order (-0.076), suggesting that higher-cost orders may be delivered marginally faster, though this relationship is minimal.
  2. The rating variable demonstrates a weak positive correlation with cost of the order (0.034), indicating that customers may tend to rate more expensive orders slightly higher. However, the correlation is not strong enough to suggest a consistent pattern.
  3. Correlations between rating and both food preparation time and delivery time are nearly zero, implying that customer feedback is not significantly influenced by logistical metrics alone.

These findings indicate that customer ratings are likely driven by factors not captured in the dataset, such as food quality, customer service, or packaging. While the cleaning step improved data integrity, the weak correlations suggest limited predictive value of the current numerical features on customer satisfaction.

Additional observations include support previous conclusions, but add the following:

  1. Distribution: The rating variable is heavily skewed toward the higher end, with the majority of ratings being 4 or 5.
  2. Cost of the Order shows a broad spread, with a slight positive skew. However, there is no visible linear trend when plotted against delivery time or preparation time
  3. Inter-variable Relationships: Scatter plots reveal no strong or obvious linear trends between most variable pairs. This visual inspection confirms the earlier correlation analysis—no significant pairwise dependencies exist among the numeric features.

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]¶

In [19]:
# Write the code here
# Define commission logic using conditions
def calculate_revenue(order_cost):
    if order_cost > 20:
        return order_cost * 0.25
    elif order_cost > 5:
        return order_cost * 0.15
    else:
        return 0

# Apply revenue calculation to each row
df1['company_revenue'] = df1['cost_of_the_order'].apply(calculate_revenue)

# Calculate total revenue
total_revenue = df1['company_revenue'].sum()

# Display result
print(f"Total revenue generated by the company: ${total_revenue:.2f}")

Total revenue generated by the company: $6166.30

Observations: Based on the company’s tiered commission structure— 25% on orders above $20 and 15% on orders above $5— the total net revenue generated from all qualifying orders in the dataset is $6,166.30. This approach allows the company to maximize revenue from high-value orders while still capturing earnings from mid-range transactions. It highlights that a significant portion of revenue is driven by customers who place larger orders, suggesting that promoting high-value meals or bundles could further enhance profitability.¶

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]¶

Conclusions:¶

  1. Leverage High-Rated Restaurants in Promotions Restaurants like The Meatball Shop, Shake Shack, and Blue Ribbon Fried Chicken consistently received high ratings with substantial order volume.
  2. Optimize Delivery Efficiency The average total time (prep + delivery) is often above 45 minutes, and longer delivery times can impact ratings.
  3. Enhance Weekend Cuisine Options American and Fast Food dominate on weekends, indicating user preference.
  4. Incentivize Feedback ~39% of orders are missing customer ratings, which limits the ability to assess satisfaction.
  5. Upsell Based on Order Value Trends About 29% of orders exceed $20, contributing to higher platform revenue via commission.
  6. Target High-Value, Frequent Customers A small number of customers place a disproportionately high number of orders.
  7. Optimize Underperforming Cuisines Cuisines such as Vietnamese, Spanish, Korean, and Southern appear at the bottom of the order volume, indicating either lower demand, limited availability, or under-promotion.

Recommendations: (Numbers 1 - 7 align with conclusions above)¶

  1. Recommendation: Highlight these restaurants in app banners or special promotions. Consider exclusive loyalty points or discounts for returning to these top-rated venues.
  2. Recommendation: Analyze routes, improve batching logic, or partner with more efficient delivery partners to reduce delivery time, especially for popular restaurants.
  3. Recommendation: Curate weekend-specific combos or offer discounts on top weekend cuisines. Use push notifications on Friday/Saturday evenings to promote these.
  4. Recommendation: Offer small incentives (e.g., loyalty points or future discounts) to customers who rate their orders—especially for new restaurants or low-engagement users.
  5. Recommendation: Use recommendation engines to upsell add-ons or bundled meals to nudge lower-spend users toward the $20+ mark (where platform margin increases).
  6. Recommendation: Establish a VIP loyalty tier for top 5–10% customers offering exclusive rewards, early access to new restaurants, or free delivery.
  7. Recommendation: Review vendor availability, quality, pricing, and delivery performance. Remove or improve underperforming partners to preserve brand trust.
